40|$|Recent {{studies on}} the {{organization}} of space seek to define the nature of monuments within a local context. This approach to monumental space requires a distinction between monuments and landscapes, where the latter is merely a setting for the former. This thesis challenges the above distinction, and recognizes that terraces are monumental constructed landscapes. As monuments, terraces compete with their surroundings {{as well as with}} similar structures at other sites. The monumental Cimon terrace under the Parthenon on the Athenian Acropolis is a case study, and its relationship with its surrounding monuments and with terraces at Delphi and Persepolis is explored. The terraces are compared based on their implied <b>investment</b> <b>index</b> values, a calculated ratio of the maximum volume of stone to the area of the horizontal space. In comparison to terraces at Delphi and Persepolis, the implied <b>investment</b> <b>index</b> value of the Cimon terrace is the largest, and therefore the Cimon terrace is the largest expression of power between the sites...|$|R
