50|$|In 1965, {{the party}} {{approved}} the New Economic Model, {{which had been}} drafted {{under the direction of}} economist and theoretician Ota Šik. The program called for a second, intensive stage of economic development, emphasizing technological and managerial improvements. Central planning would be limited to overall production and <b>investment</b> <b>indexes</b> as well as price and wage guidelines. Management personnel would be involved in decision-making. Production would be market oriented and geared toward profitability. Prices would respond to supply and demand. Wage differentials would be introduced.|$|R
